.TH PLPTEX3 3plplot  "August, 2007" "" "PLplot API"
.SH NAME
\fBplptex3\fP - Write text inside the viewport of a 3D plot. 
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBplptex3\fP(\fIx\fP, \fIy\fP, \fIz\fP, \fIdx\fP, \fIdy\fP, \fIdz\fP, \fIsx\fP, \fIsy\fP, \fIsz\fP, \fIjust\fP, \fItext\fP)
.SH DESCRIPTION

.P
Writes text at a specified position and inclination within the viewport.  Text is clipped at the viewport boundaries.  The reference point of a string lies along a line passing through the string at half the height of a capital letter.  The position of the reference point along this line is determined by \fIjust\fP, the reference point is placed at world coordinates (\fIx\fP, \fIy\fP,\fIz\fP) within  the viewport. The inclination and shear of the string is specified in  terms of differences of world coordinates making it easy to write text  parallel to a line in a graph. 
.P
Redacted form:  General: \fBplptex3(x, y, z, dx, dy, dz, sx, sy, sz,  just, text) \fP
F95, Java, Perl/PDL, Python: \fBNot implemented.\fP

.P
This function is not used in any examples. 
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
\fIx\fP (PLFLT, input) 
x coordinate of reference point of string. 
.TP
\fIy\fP (PLFLT, input) 
y coordinate of reference point of string. 
.TP
\fIz\fP (PLFLT, input) 
z coordinate of reference point of string. 
.TP
\fIdx\fP (PLFLT, input) 
Together with \fIdy\fP,\fIdz\fP, this specifies the inclination of  the string.  The baseline of the string is parallel to a line  joining (\fIx\fP,\fIy\fP, \fIz\fP) to (\fIx\fP+\fIdx\fP, \fIy\fP+\fIdy\fP, \fIz\fP+\fIdz\fP). 
.TP
\fIdy\fP (PLFLT, input) 
Together with \fIdx\fP, \fIdy\fP, this specifies the inclination of the string. 
.TP
\fIdz\fP (PLFLT, input) 
Together with \fIdx\fP, \fIdy\fP, this specifies the inclination of the string. 
.TP
\fIsx\fP (PLFLT, input) 
Together with \fIsy\fP,\fIsz\fP, this specifies the shear of  the string.  The string is sheared so that the characters are  vertically parallel to a line joining (\fIx\fP,\fIy\fP, \fIz\fP) to (\fIx\fP+\fIsx\fP, \fIy\fP+\fIsy\fP, \fIz\fP+\fIsz\fP). If \fIsx\fP=\fIsy\fP =\fIsz\fP=0) then the text is not sheared. 
.TP
\fIsy\fP (PLFLT, input) 
Together with \fIsx\fP, \fIsy\fP, this specifies shear of the string. 
.TP
\fIsz\fP (PLFLT, input) 
Together with \fIsx\fP, \fIsy\fP, this specifies shear of the string. 
.TP
\fIjust\fP (PLFLT, input) 
Specifies the position of the string relative to its reference point.  If \fIjust\fP=0, the reference point is at the left and if \fIjust\fP=1, it is at the right of the string.  Other values of \fIjust\fP give intermediate justifications. 
.TP
\fItext\fP (const char *, input) 
The string to be written out. 

